post_text: Veterans from the American Legion Post #437 have been helping us unload tractor trailers full of food to feed those in need since March. As food supplies continue to be delivered each day, they could use some help. We will be receiving a large food delivery tomorrow, Thursday, September 3rd, at 3:00 PM, and we need as many hands as possible to move the food into our building. If you are willing/able to help for 1-2 hours, please stop by the Moshannon Valley Branch in Philipsburg around 3:00 PM. The food will be delivered at the back of the building by the baseball complex. If you have any questions or need additional information, you may call the branch at 814-342-0889 and ask for Mel Curtis. #HungerActionMonth #TheYFeedsKids

Although we face the unknown during these unprecedented times, please understand the YMCA is there for you and your family. #TheYFeedsKids

post_text: As school days draw nearer, and the summer lunch program ended last week; our focus is changing to the student backpack program for meals for the weekend. The need is very real as last year prior to COVID-19 we were providing over 1,300 backpacks to children every week. We totally understand that these numbers will be much higher this year. The food is these photos is shelf stable products, and although it may appear to be a lot, it is just a small percentage of the food that will be given out. The YMCA is committed to making sure children are feed and we will be there for them. Please help us make a difference in a child's life. #TheYFeedsKids

shared_text:
YMCA of Centre County
August 21 at 4:41 PM ·

Our 2020 Summer Lunch season has officially ended, and we'd like to send a HUGE thank you to all of the Y staff and directors who worked tirelessly to make this program a success. Whether you worked behind the scenes (the staff in our Bellefonte kitchen alone prepared over 900 meals per day!) or on the front lines, we couldn't be more appreciative of your commitment to ensuring kids in our community have the food they need to thrive - particularly during these challenging times.

Although our Summer Lunch Program is over until next summer, we continue to provide food to local kids during the school year. Our Backpack Program ensures kids in school districts across Centre County have food to eat on the weekends. Learn more about this and other services offered through our Anti-Hunger Program at the link below.
https://www.ymcaofcentrecounty.org/programs/youth-development/feeding-our-children/

post_text: I wanted to send a shout out to Stephanie Showers, who has been coordinating the Summer Lunch Program since 2004, 16 years and still going strong. I still remember the day that I hired her and she is every bit excited today as she was in 2004. There are countless hours of worrying about budget, getting food orders in to distributors, making sure everything is ready for delivery, completing monthly reports, and so much more. She has handled it and got things done. There are many people behind the scenes, or behind the mask, that people never see. As we approach the last day of the summer lunch program tomorrow, I can tell you she is thinking of ways to make it better next year. Thank you Stephanie Showers for 16 years of outstanding work, making sure food is available for children! You are a Hunger Hero! - Mel

post_text: Attendance at today's food distribution at Mountaintop Elementary School far exceeded our expectations, and we unfortunately ran out of lunches and backpacks with educational items from WPSU. While we were able to arrange to have more meals delivered to the site as soon as possible (we apologize for the extra wait), we weren't able to get more backpacks out today. We never want to have to turn anyone away from the opportunity to receive these much-needed items, so if you didn't receive a backpack, be sure to stop by the site tomorrow - more will be available for pickup then!

We were beyond honored to be invited to a very special celebration today! At the beginning of April, Jerry Gross set a goal--by his 83rd birthday, he would bike a total of 830 laps around his neighborhood and raise $830 for the Y's Anti-Hunger Program. Today Jerry biked his final 3 laps to hit 830, celebrated his birthday, and announced raising a total of $4,750!! A true hunger hero!! Thank you so much, Jerry and all who supported his FUNdraiser! Have a wonderful birthday!

post_text:
When the YMCA of Centre County Anti-Hunger Program committed to helping others, we were aware this was for the long haul. There was and still isn't a quick fix for hunger. The following studies and National Organizations have released information in reference to the impact of COVID-19.

Young children are experiencing food insecurity to an extent unprecedented in modern times. (Hamilton Project)

In April food insecurity doubled overall and tripled among households with children. (Institute for Policy Research)

Predictions of newly food insecure: additional 3.3 – 17 million (Feeding America)

Rates of summer learning loss will increase due to school closures and cuts to programs. (NWEA)

Prior to COVID-19 we saw that one in seven children were facing food insecurity, now we are seeing that number to be one in four children facing food insecurity.

post_text: So tonight the YMCA Anti-Hunger Program, Hope Fire Co, and Hi-Way Pizza was able to mobilize 4 pieces of fire equipment to deliver 196 boxes of pizza, 2 cuts per box, or a total of 392 cuts of pizza to children in the Philipsburg Area and beyond. A special thank you to Jerry the Pizza King for donating all this pizza. Jerry does amazing things for our community to help others. Thank you to Hope Fire Co and all the members for taking time out of your evening to make sure these kids would get something extra. To the YMCA Volunteers, Brenda, Jamie and Shirley for jumping in and out of trucks tonight to give the pizza to the children.Thanks to Faith for always being at the right place at the right time. To see the smiles on the kids faces made this night truly amazing and we even had cars chasing us down, it was great.In unprecedented times you need to do some innovative things to make sure kids are feed and are happy. #PhilipsburgProud #HiWayPizzaCares #TheYFeedsKids

shared_text:
DiamondBack Covers
May 7 at 7:45 PM ·

While our production lines sit idle, some of our team members have been keeping busy by lending a hand to the local YMCA, a longtime DiamondBack partner. Their food programs provide meals to hundreds of families, students, and veterans in Philipsburg and the surrounding communities.

In our neck of the woods, just like in communities everywhere, people are struggling. For too many, the next mortgage payment, or even meal, is in question. Although the objective hasn’t changed for the Moshannon Valley Y, the number of those in need has recently skyrocketed. With help from an army of volunteers, they’re answering the call.

We’re not sure what the aftermath of this shutdown will look like, or how quickly we’ll all bounce back. We do know that our neighbors are in need, and that’s unlikely to change soon. DiamondBack has partnered with the YMCA of Centre County to open DiamondBack Family Centers that will provide groceries and hot meals to those in need, far into the future.

#DiamondBackGivesBack

post_text: A new experience for the "Travelin' Table" today. After volunteers moved all the contents from one trailer to another trailer due to refrigeration problem, we got the word there was a fire in downtown Philipsburg in the business district. We had Water, Gatorade, and snacks put on the TT and we went down to give firefighters these drinks due to the higher temperatures. There was multiple fire departments here from all over Centre and Clearfield County. Everyone wanted to do it because of all the volunteering these firefighters do for the Anti-Hunger Program. Unfortunately the fire was at one of our Partners in the Anti-Hunger Program, Brown Dog Catering who supply lunches for the kids. They have been very supportive of all types of events in the Philipsburg Area. Thanks to Becky, Michelle, and Shirley for helping with this today.

shared_text:
Faith Bordas Maguire is with Cathy Lott and 5 others.
May 2 at 11:42 AM ·

What a busy Friday. Started out this morning in the Travellin Bus to Primanti Brothers to pick up lunches to hand out at the Milesburg Fire Company. We had a good crowd and had just enough lunches to feed everyone!
Then Joyce Carr and I got back in town long enough to unload the bus and check out the new painting done by The Deliman sisters! It looks gorgeous ladies! Thank you for ALL you do! We are so grateful you ladies retired! But who needs to retire?? Life is a box of chocolates! Lol!
Then We scurried down to the new Pick up station in the Old Penn Highlands Bldg next to Bio. Put on our new masked courtesy of the Screen Actors Guild of Los Angeles￼, Calif￼! How cool is that!
And we wrapped up the night handing out over 80 bags of food and 80 bags of fresh produce. What a bunch of great volunteers the Mo Valley YMCA has! It’s such a pleasure working with you all!

post_text:
NEW RELEASE

The YMCA Anti-Hunger Program, Civil Air Patrol, and Centre County Transportation are announcing today, that we will be providing Home Delivery for families and Shut-Ins that don't have the means to get to our feeding sites or Food Giveaways, This is a major undertaking that will have an impact on those that are facing food insecurity This service will be available starting the week of May 4th. This system will tracked through and planned in a GIS Program to make sure we are efficient in delivering food to all residents that have contacted us. For more information contact Mel Curtis at 814-342-0889 or mcurtis@ymcaocc.org

post_text:
CenClear Child Services plays a major role in the YMCA Anti-Hunger Program. They are a vital part of the Travelin' Table as you can see on the appearance of the logos on the bus.Their staff makes sure that the Travelin' Table is on the road and takes care of the servicing of the vehicle. Additionally, they have provided transportation services through their vans for getting food out to sites as well as box truck services in getting weekend food out to all the sites. The partnership between the YMCA and CenClear is important to the success of feeding children and also the missions of both organization parallel each other in meeting the needs of children. Thank you for everything that you do!
#CenClearCaresAboutChildren

post_text: The uniqueness of small businesses in small towns. Jennifer Patterson has followed the YMCA Anti-Hunger Program from day one when we started Emergency Feeding. She sent me a message asking if it would be okay to place a box in a business to collect donated food. She then sent out a message when she found out we needed masks for the volunteers.She has a cleaning business and when she found out we were going to open up a Family Center, she told us she wanted to clean it and get it ready. This is a person that truly cares and wants to helps others, her mission is what i call a Cause. Thank you Jennifer for all that you have done for the Anti-Hunger Program.

post_text:
Two organizations, YMCA of Centre County Anti-Hunger and Crops for Christ, have responded to this battle. While hunger is not a new enemy, the need for access to food has rapidly expanded. Together these two organizations have taken to the front lines by first expanding the YMCA’s Backpack program from weekend meals to daily lunches. With the support of multiple organizations and collaboration with Crops for Christ, the daily meal expanded to care for senior citizens and veterans. The goal is to provide for every neighbor regardless of age or circumstance, until the fight is over. Adam Clampet, who heads up Crops for Christ, was one of the initial people to go the the Bellefonte Branch with donations, traveling to pick up supplies needed, and offering total support that no one goes hungry. As a veteran, he wants to make sure that those who have served their country have the food they need for themselves and their family.
#SomeoneYouShouldKnow

post_text: The Partnership between the Central Pennsylvania Food Bank and the YMCA Anti-Hunger Program is is so crucial for the success in the work that we are doing. It's not uncommon that I pick up the phone and call either Harrisburg or Williamsport and tell them I have a tractor trailer waiting to dock at one of there locations to get 28 skids of food. As a matter of fact, that call will be going out first thing on Monday. We are fortunate to have this partnership because during these unprecedented times, we can't get the food we need to feed the kids. We have also opened up two more feeding sites in Wingate and Snow Shoe that will start this month with large scaled food available for families. The Food Bank has taken over a large portion the the Farm Show Complex in Harrisburg just to stay up with the demands for food that is needed. We have had great working relationships with CPFB from, the Travelin' Table, the Backpack Program, Fresh Express, and funding through grants. #CentralPAFoodBankCares

post_text: In these unprecedented times, emergencies, and disasters, we always know that police, fire and EMS will be there for their communities. These are the people that walk into the unknown,and these are also the people that have stepped up to help the YMCA Anti-Hunger Programs. Either by feeding children, permitting use of their grounds, transporting goods, unloading food supplies, and making sure things are under control. shared_text:
YMCA of Centre County
March 27 at 4:02 PM ·

Last week, as we prepared to temporarily close our facilities to the public, we knew we needed to act quickly to ensure we would be able to provide support for the new set of challenges our community would face. In a matter of days, we gathered the resources to begin distributing food to kids in need. Now, our facilities are filled with boxes of food, and we're providing meals to over 1,000 local kids per day at 24 drive-through sites. We can't thank those who have been donating and volunteering enough for their support. If you'd like to contribute to the cause or learn more, please visit the link below. https://www.ymcaofcentrecounty.org/ymca/anti-hunger-program-updates/

post_text:
YMCA Anti-Hunger Update:
For anyone who is currently volunteering or would like to volunteer at any of our 23 sites and warehouse, please email: antihungervolunteers@ymcaocc.org. In the content of your email, we need the following information: Name, phone #, email address, the school district area that you are willing to volunteer in, and what type of volunteer work you are willing to do (transport food to sites, volunteer at sites, volunteer for packing, or volunteer to pick-up donation). We have received a tremendous response from our community, and we want to make sure we are responding to everyone. For safety reasons, we will only be working in small groups. Please be sure to share so everyone is aware of the new process.Thank you for helping us make a difference!

post_text: On Monday we will be announcing the locations of the sites we will be serving from. These will be Drop & Go sites only. They may be much like a drive thru or a walk up. The children will take the food home with them to eat. We will be giving them a lunch and a evening snack. These sites will be located in areas that meet USDA eligibility requirements, but we will be adding more as the time goes on and as needed. This is a major undertaking for the YMCA and all of the volunteers, and we want to make sure we are doing our due diligence in making sure children are receiving food. I can't say it enough, if you are in need of food or hygiene products, please ask, we are all in this together.

shared_text:
YMCA of Centre County
March 13 at 8:52 PM ·

YMCA of Centre County’s Anti-Hunger Program is prepared to help children in need of food while schools are closed due to the Coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak. We realize that many children in our community are dependent on the meals they receive at school through the Free/Reduced Lunch Program and that these may be their main source of nutrition throughout the week.

It’s important to us to ensure that no child in our community goes hungry as a result of school closures. If you or another family in your community are struggling to put food on the table or if you are willing to provide support of any kind, please contact Mel Curtis at (814) 342-0889 or mcurtis@ymcaocc.org as soon as possible.

We’ll continue to post updates regarding our Anti-Hunger Initiatives as they become available. Thank you in advance for your support.

It’s important to us to ensure that no child in our community goes hungry as a result of school closures. If you or another family in your community are struggling to put food on the table or if you are willing to provide support of any kind, please contact Mel Curtis at (814) 342-0889 or mcurtis@ymcaocc.org as soon as possible.

We’ll continue to post updates regarding our Anti-Hunger Initiatives as they become available. Thank you in advance for your support.

https://www.ymcaofcentrecounty.org/alerts/

post_text: Although the calendar says its Winter, Summer will be here before you know it. There are thousands of children that depend on the Free/Reduced meals they get at school, but when school is out, the meals stop. We are currently looking for additional locations to serve meals to children in areas that qualify under USDA Standards. These areas are all of Centre County and parts of Clearfield County.These can be churches, fire companies, social halls or even parks. If you know of an area that would be a good location that children can get to please let me know. If your organization is interested in volunteering to help feed kids, let me know that also.Please help us make a difference in a child's life. For more information contact Mel Curtis at mcurtis@ymcaocc.org or call 814-342-0889.

Kick off December with your kids tomorrow with Hope Fire Company. Sunday, December 1st from noon to 2 PM we are hosting a ‘Brunch with a Santa’ at our Rec. Center, 500 N 6th St in Philipsburg. For just a non-perishable food item or a small monetary donation to the food bank, you and your kids can enjoy pancakes, eggs, bacon and sausage along with orange juice and our hot chocolate bar. Kids will be able to visit with Santa and write letters to him with their wish list. Thanks to our own volunteers and generous community donors, there will be no additional cost to our guests aside from the food bank donation. We hope to see you all there.

November 29, 2019 at 3:41 PM ·

Looking for some assistance, or you may know somebody who can help us, or they may know somebody, but we need to find the right people. Each year at the Moshannon Valley YMCA Branch for our Christmas Program, there are families we provide food to. It would be great if we could find a large number of these reusable bags to put the food in, it has handles to carry, and they can be used repeatedly. In the past we have always used boxes, but they are getting hard to find because as businesses empty the contents they cut them down so they don’t take as much space.
Hopefully we can find enough businesses that would be willing to donate to this Christmas project. Contact Mel Curtis at 814-342-0889 or mcurtis@ymcaocc.org
